</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Re "Eastin Strikes Conciliatory Note," Nov. 10: 
</P>
<P>
 How strange. Jean Merl points out that Maureen DiMarco, the loser for 
superintendent of public instruction, will continue in her appointed office as 
Gov. Pete Wilson's education policy adviser along with the Wilson-appointed 
State Board of Education; and it is the elected winner, Delaine Eastin, who 
will be expected to "seek compromise."Appointees have more clout than elected 
officials? Why?! 
</P>
