 Why should someone elected to office by about the same percentage of votes 
(56%) as the governor (55%) have to seek compromise with a group of appointees 
on whom voters had no say? The one appointee the voters could vote on -- 
DiMarco -- was defeated. Surely Wilson is looking for a different education 
policy adviser -- the voters don't want this one. 
</P>
<P>
