<HEADLINE>
<P>
PREP TENNIS / CITY SECTION FINALS; PALISADES TOPS TAFT IN GIRLS 4-A 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG SANDOVAL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 After winning the last two City Section Division 4-A girls' team tennis titles 
with young teams, Woodland Hills Taft High was favored to win the championship 
this year with a squad of seniors. 
</P>
<P>
 Instead, Palisades upset the Toreadors, 6-1, at the Universal Racquet Centre 
in Studio City on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Before the final, Palisades Coach Bud Kling said his team had an even chance 
of winning, but he was worried how his No. 2 doubles team would play after one 
of the girls, Jennie Wilson, suffered an injury. 
</P>
<P>
 Kling went to his junior varsity team for a substitute, selecting Christin 
Cho. 
</P>
<P>
 "Cho played really solid tennis for us," Kling said. "She wasn't intimidated 
and really played aggressively."  
</P>
<P>
 Cho and Alison Fischer easily won the No. 2 doubles match, 6-4, 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
 In the 3-A final, Carson's 5-2 victory over Eagle Rock was clinched when its 
No. 1 doubles team of Jessica Quileza and Christina Banania hung on for a 6-0, 
6-7 (7-5), 6-3 victory over Jenny Gonzales and Alice Shen. GREG SANDOVAL 
</P>
