<HEADLINE>
<P>
DEALS: COMPANY TOWN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN LIPPMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Cable: Tele-Communications Inc. said its board approved a plan Thursday that 
would divide the Denver-based cable TV giant into four separate companies. TCI 
Chief Executive John C. Malone said the new structure would give the company 
greater financial and strategic flexibility while still providing "synergies 
and scale economics provided by a common corporate parent."Under the plan, 
first outlined in March, TCI would divide itself into separate companies 
encompassing domestic cable operations and telephony, programming, 
international investments and technology. Shareholders would be able to invest 
in TCI or in any of the four other entities. TCI would maintain a controlling 
interest in each of the four companies, however. TCI said shareholder approval 
is expected by spring. A TCI spokesman said the plan would allow the investment 
community to "appropriately value" the assets of the company. TCI, the largest 
cable TV operator in the country, serves about 13 million subscribers. JOHN 
LIPPMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
