<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: CAMARILLO; GIRL TESTIFIES IN TRIAL OF TEACHER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BARBARA MURPHY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Camarillo teen-ager testified Thursday that she willingly engaged in sexual 
conduct with her church teacher but stopped short of intercourse because of her 
fear that she would become pregnant. 
</P>
<P>
 The 14-year-old girl testified for a full day in the child molestation trial 
of Robert C. Rose. She cried at times as she described how their relationship 
developed from friendship to romance, starting with a kiss exchanged in the 
recreation hall at St. Mary Magdalen Church. 
</P>
<P>
 At the time, Rose, 49, was director of the church's youth religion education 
program. He is charged with 10 counts of child molestation for incidents 
alleged to have occurred between January and April, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 The girl testified that she met Rose in September, 1992, and became 
increasingly fond of him as he took an interest in her life. Soon he was 
calling her on the phone four times a week, she said. 
</P>
<P>
 "He was more like a teen-ager," she said, when asked by Deputy Dist. Atty. 
Saundra T. Brewer what she thought of Rose. "He was an adult that we could 
understand and that we could talk to in our way." 
</P>
<P>
 The girl said that on three occasions, Rose parked his car behind a building 
while giving her a ride home from church and they fondled each other. She 
testified that she did not resist Rose's sexual advances. 
</P>
<P>
 "I liked what was happening," she said. "I never thought it was wrong." 
</P>
<P>
 She said she finally got scared when Rose drove her to his work, undressed her 
and himself, and began kissing and touching her. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wasn't ready to go further," she testified. "I felt like it might have gone 
(further), and I wasn't ready." 
</P>
<P>
 Superior Court Judge Ken W. Riley adjourned court early after concluding that 
several hours on the witness stand had tired the girl. She is scheduled to 
resume her testimony Tuesday. BARBARA MURPHY 
</P>
</TEXT>
