<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION GIRLS' TENNIS PLAYOFF ROUNDUP; EL DORADO TOPPLES TOP-SEEDED 
HEMET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MELANIE NEFF 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 El Dorado girls' tennis coach John Cyrus used football to motivate his team in 
its upset of No. 1-seeded Hemet Thursday in the Southern Section Division III 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
 The match ended in a 9-9 tie, but the Golden Hawks, who lost in last year's 
semifinals to North Hollywood Harvard-Westlake, won on games, 82-75. 
</P>
<P>
 Cyrus, a former football coach, gave a brief speech to the girls before they 
took the courts and used the Golden Hawks football disqualification from the 
Southern Section playoffs, for using an ineligible player, as motivation.  
</P>
<P>
 "Our football team . . . overcame a lot of things this season and they had it 
all taken away," Cyrus told his team. "It's not fair. So let's do this for the 
football team." 
</P>
<P>
 The match came down to the final two sets, with the scored tied, 8-8, and El 
Dorado ahead in games 71-66. 
</P>
<P>
 El Dorado's Linda Surapruik rallied in her final set against Jennifer Barnes, 
winning four consecutive games for a 6-3 victory that gave the Golden Hawks a 
9-8 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 El Dorado's No. 1 doubles team of Susan Surapruik and Brittany McMillan forced 
Hemet's Kristen Barnes and Ellen Cheeseman to a tiebreaker, where Barnes and 
Cheeseman were able to get the victory for the Bulldogs (20-3), but Surapruik 
and McMillan gave the Golden Hawks the games needed to win the match. 
</P>
<P>
 Surapruik and McMillan gave the Golden Hawks (21-5) two of their three 
victories in doubles with scores of 6-3, 6-2, 6-7.  
</P>
<P>
 In singles, Michelle Weisz easily swept her sets, 6-2, 6-0, 6-1, and Linda 
Surapruik also swept, 7-5, 6-1, 6-3, for El Dorado. 
</P>
<P>
 El Dorado will face Pasadena Poly in the Southern Section final at 10 a.m. 
Tuesday at the Claremont Tennis Club. MELANIE NEFF 
</P>
</TEXT>
